\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Infinite diameter confidence sets in Hedges’ publication bias model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Introduction.

\series default
 Talk about publication bias and why it is important.
 Add one paragraph about impossibility theorems in frequentist statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Hedges' publication bias model.

\series default
 Talk about this model specifically.
 Explain why it is exactly what we want.
 Name some applications.
 Make a plot showing how it can go bad.
 Show how this can affect estimates and confidence sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Confidence sets of infinite diameter.
 
\series default
A technical section introducing the concepts.
 Connec the partitions to Hedges' model, and state the modified Gleser–Hwang
 theorem; include an example from Gleser–Hwang and from the Berger paper.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Infinite diameter in Hedges' model.
 
\series default
Start with infinite diameters in the full selection for significance model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Appendix.
 
\series default
Proofs and so on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Talk about one-sided selection and why (two sentences?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hedges' publication bias model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most popular and well-known meta-analysis method is the random effects
 model with normal likelihoods (Borenstein).
 Written in hierarchical notation, it equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\theta & \sim & N(\theta_{0},\tau),\\
x_{i}\mid\theta,\sigma & \sim & N(\theta,\sqrt{\tau^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th study.
 Following the convention in meta-analysis, we assume these parameters to
 be known.
 The mean parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the population effect size, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\theta_{0},\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the effect size distribution.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the heterogeneity parameter.
 The purpose of the effect size distribution is to model the fact that most
 effect size estimates plugged into a meta-analysis do not appear to come
 from exactly the same phenomenon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the simplest of these models, only significant results are observed.
 In this case,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x;\theta_{0},\sigma_{i})=\Phi\left(\frac{\theta_{0}-c_{\alpha}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}+\tau}}\right)^{-1}\phi(x;\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}),\label{eq:selection for significance model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}=\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for some significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model was introduced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hedges1984estimation"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in the context of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-distributions.
 It is the underlying model of the estimating 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-curve, popular in psychology.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}})\propto\phi(x_{i};\theta_{0},(\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2})^{1/2})w(u)\label{eq:hedges model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To model this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be a vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\alpha_{0}<\alpha_{1}<\ldots<\alpha_{K}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-ary non-negative, non-increasing vector satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{K}=1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w(u;\rho,\alpha)=\sum_{k=1}^{K}\rho_{k}1_{(\alpha_{j-1},\alpha_{j}]}(u)\label{eq:step function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is non-increasing since a publication decision based solely on 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values should always act favourably towards higher 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-values.
 This assumption allows us to write Hedges' model as a mixture model.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x_{i};\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}})=\sum_{k=1}^{K}\pi^{k}f^{k}(x_{i};\theta_{0},(\tau^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{1/2}),\label{eq:mixture model formulation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{K}$
\end_inset

 is a normal density, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{k},k<K$
\end_inset

 are normal densities truncated to 
\begin_inset Formula $[\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha_{j-1}),\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha))$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}$
\end_inset

 are the mixture probabilities, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}>0$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=1}^{K}\pi^{k}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The mixture probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{k}$
\end_inset

 are functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\theta_{0},\tau,\sigma_{i},\rho)$
\end_inset

, see the appendix page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "eq:pi_i formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for their formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedge's publication bias models 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value based publication bias directly, there is no approximation involved.
 If you believe in the random effects meta-analysis model and the 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-value based publication bias scenario described above, Hedge's publication
 bias model is simply the correct model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can not be said for the other statistical methods correcting for publicatio
n bias in the literature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PET-PEESE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimating 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-curve and 
\emph on
p
\emph default
-uniform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trim-and-fill
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Confidence sets of infinite diameter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fix some measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a family of dominated probability measures defined on this measurable
 space, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\Pi}$
\end_inset

 a partitioning of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that a partioning of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of disjoint non-empty subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{\pi\in\Pi}\pi=\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

, we will use the standard notation 
\begin_inset Formula $[P]$
\end_inset

 to denote the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:confidence set"

\end_inset

 A 
\emph on
confidence set
\emph default
 of level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a family of rejection sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\{R(\pi)\},\pi\in\Pi$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sup_{\pi\in\Pi}\sup_{P\in\pi}P(R(\pi))\leq\alpha.\label{eq:confidence set}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the inequality is an equality, the confidence set has 
\emph on
size
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition of confidence sets might look slightly unfamiliar, but it
 is a straight-forward generalization of the definitions in e.g.
 Lehmann and Romano.
 Often, a confidence set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{0}\in C\iff\omega\notin R(\pi_{0}),\label{eq:c-confidence set}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

 if and only if accept the null-hypothesis 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:\pi=\pi_{0}$
\end_inset

, but we will only need the formulation using rejection sets in this paper.
 Often when confidence sets are defined in terms of rejection sets, there
 is no partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 to take the supremum over, and the definition reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{P\in\mathcal{P}}P(R(P))\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The terminology 
\emph on
confidence interval
\emph default
 is far more common than confidence set, but this requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:c-confidence set"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is an interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following example should make Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:confidence set"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 familiar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:t-test"

\end_inset

 Consider the usual 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 contains all measures 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu,\sigma}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu,\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the probability measure of a normal with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\mu)=\{P_{\mu,\sigma}^{n}\mid\sigma>0\}$
\end_inset

 contain all normal probability measures with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and some positive standard deviation.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\mu),\mu\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval is a confidence set of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 according to definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:confidence set"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we must find out how to measure the size of confidence sets.
 Let a size function be any positive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert :\Pi\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 In the 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval example above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 can be taken to be the absolute value of the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 associated with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diameter of a confidence set is the random variable
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(\omega)=\sup_{\pi\in\Pi}\{\left\Vert \pi\right\Vert \mid\omega\notin R(\pi)\}\label{eq:diameter}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the diameter tells you the size of the largest accepted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is Borel measurable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A confidence set has infinite diameter with 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

-positive probability if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D=\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 It has infinite diameter with positive probability if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D=\infty)>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theorem is a slight generalization of the Gleser–Hwang theorem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Gleser--Hwang"

\end_inset

 Suppose there is a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of densities from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the following: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
There is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\star}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\star}$
\end_inset

 pointwise ,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\supp p\supseteq\supp p^{\star}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the size of 
\begin_inset Formula $[p_{i}]$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert [p_{i}]\right\Vert \to\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Theorem
Then every confidence set with level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 has infinite diameter with positive probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
See the appendix, page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "proof:Gleser--Hwang"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some possible candidates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi$
\end_inset

 in the publication bias model.
 We will consider three of them.
 First, the partitioning where 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\pi$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

 have the same mean effect size parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We will equip this partitioning with the size function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \pi\right\Vert =|\theta_{0}|$
\end_inset

, and it corresponds to a confidence set for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Second, consider the partitioning where all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\pi$
\end_inset

 have the same heterogeneity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, equipped with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \pi\right\Vert =\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, we will work with the partitioning where all 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\pi$
\end_inset

 have the same heterogeneity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and population effect size 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

, and equip it with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \pi\right\Vert =\sqrt{\theta_{0}^{2}+\tau^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 This information is summarised in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Possible partitions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for convenience.
 
\end_layout

